            <hr>
            <h2>Lesson 2: HTML Attributes</h2>
            <h3>Attributes</h3>
            <p>An "attribute" is a value placed inside the <b>opening tag</b> of an HTML element. Attributes provide additional information about the element or specify how the element should behave. The standard syntax for an attribute is:</p>
            <code>&lt;element attribute="value"&gt;&lt;/element&gt;</code>
            <p>Common attributes and their purposes include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>href</code> : Used within <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> to specify destination URL of a link</li>
                <li><code>target</code> : Used within <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> to specify where to open link E.g:
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>target="_blank"</code> enables the link to open in a new tab</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><code>src</code> : Used within <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> to specify the source of an image</li>
                <li><code>alt</code> : Used within <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> to provide alternative descriptive text for the image</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="index.html" target="_blank">Open homepage in new tab</a>
            <img src="data/dungeon_game.png" alt="Screenshot of my dungeon game project" />
            <p>Some attributes such as <code>href</code> and <code>src</code> are <b>required</b>. Whereas others are not.</p>
            <p>Some attributes are don't require an "atribute=..." part. For example the <code>checked</code> attribute of <code>&lt;input type="checkbox" checked&gt;</code> controls whether a checkbox is checked by default. Since this is a <b>boolean attribute</b> the presence of "<code>checked</code>" or lack of is sufficient</p>
            <input type="checkbox" checked />
            <p>Other boolean attributes commonly encountered are <code>disabled</code>, <code>readonly</code> and <code>required</code>. These attributes are used to specify whether a certain element is disabled, read-only or required.</p>
            <p>For example:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Here is a text <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> element that is disabled by default:<input type="text" disabled></li>
                <li>Here is a text <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> element that isn't disabled by default:<input type="text"></li>
            </ul>
        </section>
